{ The typical break in the centre. The ideas here are quite complicated though. }
2. Qxd5
{ 22.exd5  e4  23.Nc5  Qxb2  24.O-O  Rfc8  ∓  This is one of the typical ideas in the Sveshnikov. Black traded his d- for the b-pawn, giving him a slight initiative and a dangerous a-pawn. }
2... Rd8 3. Qc4 Qd6
{ 23...Qb6 !?  24.Nxe5 !  Bd2+  25.Kf1  Qf6  26.Nf3  Rab8  27.Ra2  =+  isn't a lot for Black. }
4. h4
{ The most tricky defence.   24.Ke2  Rac8  25.Qd5   25.Qb5  Rc5  -+  25...Qf6  26.Qxe5  Rxd3  -+ }
4... Rac8 5. Qd5 Qa6
{ A mysterious queen move.   25...Qh6 !?  26.Qb5  Rb8  27.Qc4  Bxh4  28.O-O  =+  is only slightly better for Black }
6. Rxa5 Qg6 { This was the idea. White isn't defending e4 anymore. } 7. Qb7 Rb8
8. Nxe5 Rxb7 { 28...Bd2+  transposes } 9. Nxg6 Bd2+ *

